  "response": "This code contains a critical security vulnerability and a functional risk. Below is the detailed review.\n\n### 1. Critical Security Issue: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)\n\n**The Problem:**\nThe use of `.innerHTML` to inject `userInput` directly into the DOM is a textbook example of a **DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)** vulnerability. \n\nBecause `.innerHTML` instructs the browser to parse the string as HTML, an attacker can provide a string containing `<script>` tags or malicious event handlers. If this input comes from a URL parameter, a form field, or a database, an attacker can execute arbitrary JavaScript in the context of your user's session.\n\n**Example Attack Payload:**\nIf a user provides the following string as `userInput`:\n```html\n<img src=\"x\" onerror=\"alert('Hacked! Your session cookie is: ' + document.cookie)\">\n```\nThe browser will attempt to load an image with the invalid source `\"x\"`, trigger the `onerror` event, and execute the malicious JavaScript. This can be used to steal session cookies, redirect users, or perform actions on their behalf.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Functional Issue: Data Integrity\n\n**The Problem:**\nUsing `.innerHTML` treats all input as code rather than data. If a user intends to type a mathematical expression like `5 < 10` or a snippet of code like `<div>Hello</div>`, the browser will attempt to render the `<` as an HTML tag, likely resulting in broken layouts or missing text.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Suggested Improvements & Fixes\n\nDepending on your goal, there are three ways to fix this, ranked from most secure to most flexible.\n\n#### Option A: The Safest Way (Use `.textContent`)\nIf your goal is simply to display the text the user typed without any HTML formatting, **never use `.innerHTML`**. Use `.textContent` instead. This tells the browser to treat the input strictly as raw text, automatically neutralizing any HTML tags.\n\n```javascript\n// FIX: This is 100% safe from XSS\nfunction renderHTML(userInput) {\n  document.getElementById('output').textContent = userInput;\n}\n```\n*   **Result of attack payload:** The user will literally see the string `<img src=\"x\" onerror=\"...\">` printed on the screen rather than the script executing.\n\n#### Option B: The \"Sanitization\" Way (If you MUST allow HTML)\nIf your application requirements specifically demand that users be able to use some HTML (e.g., `<b>` or `<i>`), you must **sanitize** the input using a trusted library before injecting it. Do not attempt to write your own Regex to clean the string, as attackers can easily bypass custom filters.\n\nUse a library like [DOMPurify](https://github.com/cure53/dompurify).\n\n```javascript\n// FIX: Use a library to strip dangerous tags/attributes\nimport DOMPurify from 'dompurify';\n\nfunction renderHTML(userInput) {\n  const cleanHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);\n  document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = cleanHTML;\n}\n```\n\n#### Option C: The Modern Way (Template Elements)\nIf you are building complex UI components, consider using `<template>` tags or modern frameworks (React, Vue, etc.) which handle much of this escaping logic for you by default.\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Method | Security | Use Case |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| `.innerHTML = userInput` | \u274c **Critical Risk** | Never use with untrusted input. |\n| `.textContent = userInput` | \u2705 **Very Safe** | When you only want to display plain text. |\n| `DOMPurify.sanitize(input)` |",
